B0$ We lost a few wickets at the top, so the plan was to take the game a little deep. I have been with the team for a long time and when you get back-to-back opportunities you gotta grab it. The wicket was slightly tough at the start and the plan was to build some partnership and then target a few bowlers. I also speak to senior players who keep telling me to make sure that I take the game deep and make it big when I get a start. Really thankful to the management for the opportunities.

formatValue: Prabhsimran Singh | Player of the Match:

commText: B0$ The way the bowlers brought us back in the game it was amazing. All credit to our spinners and also our fast bowlers as well. It was turning from 4th over and playing that kind of knock is just incredible and amazing from Prabhsimran. That knock actually helped us reach that total. I told Harpreet to keep it slow and target the wickets and the way he stood up and took those wickets and especially getting those left-handers out was really fantastic. When I'm with the youngsters I try to stay young and feels good that the boys have taken responsibility and the maturity as well. Very happy the way they are growing and maturing. This win has brought a lot of confidence for us. We need to stay calm and not get too excited. Staying calm has helped us and need to do the job in the next couple of games.

commText: B0$ I enjoyed bowling on this surface. I leaked 13 runs in the first over, I was a bit nervous. I had belief that I could come back on this kind of a surface. In the first over, the ball was stopping a little and the batters were playing easily off the back foot. I tried to bowl it fuller in my spell and make the batter commit on the front foot. When you play on a slow wicket, the powerplay is crucial. DC had a good powerplay. But Rahul bowled well from the other end and he put pressure on the batters, that helped me to get the wickets. We both had in our mind to bowl as many dot balls as possible and create pressure on the batters.

B0$It was about trying to restrict them to a decent total. They got more than we would have liked. Prabhsimran batted really well, dropped chances cost us a few. At the end of the day after the powerplay when you lose 6 for 30 not going to win a lot of games. You got to play for pride, and play with freedom [on the remaining games]. Another disappointing effort with the bat after the good start we had. When you lose they are the things that happen in this format [on chopping and changing of their team]. We found the right combination but we keep losing 3-4 quick wickets and you can't do that at this level.

Yes, there was massive spin on offer and had the batters hopping front and back, but with the kind of start Delhi got, one would feel they lacked game-awareness and fell like a pack of cards, displaying some horrid footwork while at it. But, that can change tonight – a loss for Punjab Kings will compound matters for them while a loss for Delhi Capitals will end their campaign. These two sides are facing for the first time this season. In the last four games these sides have played against each other, DC have won all of them. "This is not new for us." 
 
Wasim Jaffer, Punjab Kings' batting coach, exclaimed about his team's position with a frustrated smile. With only three league games left for them, they've fallen slightly behind in the mid-table slug-fight following their successive defeats against Mumbai Indians and Kolkata Knight Riders. Currently placed eighth, another loss in Delhi on Saturday could prove extremely costly, possibly even spell the end of their playoff qualification chances. 
 
For Delhi Capitals, it's a much easier equation even if more stressful - win to stay alive. In what has possibly been the most closely-contested season of IPL so far, David Warner's team could be the first to end their qualification possibilities. 
 
 
In a way, that seemed the most obvious scenario following their four-game losing start. But they earned themselves a breather with four wins in their next five matches. However, yet another uninspiring batting display against Chennai Super Kings further dimmed their chances. A loss on Saturday will all but push them out of the reckoning, as they can only get to a maximum of 12 points for the season with two wins in the remaining games. Even if they pull that off, they will need a few uncontrollables - like results of the other top-four aspirants - to go their way for them to even stand a chance of finishing fourth. 
 
Despite the recent victory run, the concerns haven't changed. Their Indian batters have not been firing. And the only one who is - Axar Patel - continues to be used lower down the order, limiting his effectiveness. To make matters worse, David Warner, who was scoring runs - even if not at his destructive best - has found the going tough in recent games. He has enjoyed batting against Punjab Kings in the past, and would hope to replicate that success again in the must-win game.
